limitations: [
	{
		description: "Shared-schema with RLS introduces runtime overhead — every query has additional WHERE/policy evaluation. For complex relationship graphs: RLS policy may be slow."
		alternative: "Index optimization: tenant_id and relationship foreign keys indexed. RLS policy: simple IN clause on indexed columns (fast). Complex graph traversal: pre-compute visibility set (materialized view refreshed periodically). Monitor: RLS query overhead as % of total query time. If >10%: optimize policy or consider schema-per-tenant for problematic tables."
		rationale: "RLS overhead is typically <5% for simple policies on indexed columns. Complex policies: pre-compute. Performance vs security: always choose security, then optimize performance."
	},
	{
		description: "Relationship-based access (ReBAC) is more complex to implement than simple RBAC. Debugging 'why can't user X see resource Y' requires traversing relationship graph."
		alternative: "Access explanation API: GET /debug/access?user=X&resource=Y → returns: 'User X belongs to Org A. Org A has no relationship with resource Y's owner Org B. Access: denied.' Available only in development/staging. Simplifies debugging without exposing in production."
		rationale: "ReBAC is more correct for multisided platforms but harder to debug. Access explanation tool: necessary for developer productivity."
	},
	{
		description: "Per-tenant agent session isolation reduces throughput — session setup/teardown overhead × number of tenants."
		alternative: "Parallel per-tenant sessions: process tenants concurrently in separate isolated sessions. Throughput: limited by parallelism capacity, not by sequential session overhead. For scoring: 10 parallel sessions processing 10 tenants simultaneously."
		rationale: "Isolation > throughput. Parallelism recovers most throughput loss while maintaining isolation."
	},
	{
		description: "Sharing matrix becomes complex as platform grows — more entity types, more relationships, more data fields. Matrix of 50 fields × 5 participant types × 3 visibility levels = 750 cells to maintain."
		alternative: "Default: invisible. Explicit: visible. Only document visibility grants, not denials. Matrix lists what IS shared, not what isn't (shorter). Group fields by sensitivity level: public (name, status), relational (compliance, performance), private (bank account, internal notes). Sensitivity level has default visibility per participant type."
		rationale: "Default-deny + explicit-grant: matrix lists exceptions, not every cell. Sensitivity levels: reduce 750 cells to ~15 rules."
	},
	{
		description: "Audit trail at the level of every read generates enormous log volume — 100 users × 50 queries/day × 365 days = 1.8M entries/year."
		alternative: "Tiered audit logging: Tier 1 (always): mutations (writes, approvals, rejections), elevated access, admin actions, agent decisions. Tier 2 (sampled or triggered): reads of sensitive data (financial values, compliance docs). Tier 3 (on-demand): general reads (list views, dashboard loads). Full audit for Tier 1 + sampled Tier 2 = 90% compliance value at 20% of volume."
		rationale: "Full read audit is ideal but volume-intensive. Tiered approach: always audit what matters most (mutations, sensitive reads), sample the rest."
	},
]

rationale: "A Mesh é plataforma B2B multisided onde fornecedores, construtoras e FIDC compartilham infraestrutura mas requerem isolamento rigoroso — um vazamento de dados entre tenants destrói a confiança na rede. Esta lens operacionaliza: modelo de tenant com shared-schema + PostgreSQL RLS + relationship-based access para isolamento database-enforced (Bezos 2002, tenant-aware 2023+), modelo de visibilidade com data projections por participante e information asymmetry by design (ReBAC Zanzibar 2019, data projection 2023+, information asymmetry 2024+), identidade e autorização com user→org→role + org-scoped permissions + API key management (organization-scoped roles 2023+, API key identity 2024+), patterns de compartilhamento com sharing matrix e minimum necessary + consent-based (controlled sharing 2023+, consent-based 2024+), escopo de tenant para agentes IA com service accounts e session isolation (agent identity scoping 2024+), testes de isolamento como CI gate com regression blocking (isolation testing 2023+, regression 2024+), lifecycle de organização com graceful offboarding (graceful offboarding 2024+), e audit trail multi-tenant com comprehensive logging e anomaly detection (comprehensive audit 2023+, tenant-scoped audit 2024+). Específica para multisided B2B financial platforms onde data isolation é existential — failure mode é not degraded experience but destroyed trust and legal liability."

